-joint decision-making;
-timely corrective actions.

Explain:
adaptation of methods;
participant-centred approaches;
accessible learning environments;
removal of participation barriers.

Explain:
individual support measures;
accessible communication;
language support where needed;
continuous feedback and adaptation.

Explain:
communication platforms;
collaborative workspaces;
document sharing;
online coordination.

Explain:
blended learning approaches;
interactive online learning;
digital educational resources;
continued learning between physical meetings.

writing_guidance:
By the time evaluators reach this question, they already know:
the project needs;
the project objectives;
the work packages;
the planned activities;
the expected results.
Now they want to understand:
How will the consortium demonstrate that those objectives have actually been achieved?
A good assessment system normally combines several sources of evidence, including:
quantitative indicators;
qualitative indicators;
participant feedback;
partner monitoring;
project outputs;
dissemination indicators;
impact assessment.
Rather than relying on one evaluation method, strong Erasmus+ projects use a combination of tools that allow continuous monitoring during implementation and a final assessment at the end of the project.

criteria.elements:
Explain how the consortium will:
monitor progress regularly;
assess each project objective separately;
evaluate activities and work packages;
conduct interim and final evaluations;
involve all partners in the evaluation process.

Describe how the project will use:
qualitative indicators;
quantitative indicators;
participant feedback;
learning outcomes;
implementation data;
project outputs;
dissemination performance;
stakeholder feedback.
Explain that multiple sources of evidence will be compared to obtain a reliable assessment.

Explain how evaluation findings will be used to:
improve ongoing implementation;
adjust activities when necessary;
strengthen project quality;
inform future work packages;
enhance sustainability and future initiatives;
share lessons learned among partners.

writing_guidance:
By the time evaluators reach this question, they already know:
the project objectives;
the planned activities;
the expected results;
the dissemination strategy;
the expected impact.
Now they want to understand:
How will these achievements continue creating value in the future?
Sustainability in Erasmus+ usually includes several dimensions:
organisational sustainability;
educational sustainability;
partnership sustainability;
financial sustainability;
exploitation of results;
long-term community impact.
A strong answer normally combines several of these dimensions rather than focusing on only one.

criteria.elements:
Explain how participation will contribute to:
improved organisational capacity;
enhanced staff competences;
new working methods;
stronger international cooperation;
improved quality of future projects and services;
increased innovation within the organisations.

Describe how partners will:
continue using the educational resources;
integrate project methodologies into their daily work;
incorporate materials into future training programmes;
adapt the results for new target groups;
update and improve the resources when appropriate.

Explain how the project will continue benefiting:
new learners;
educators;
organisations;
local communities;
policy makers;
stakeholders;
future Erasmus+ projects.
Mention continued dissemination, transferability, and the possibility of replicating the project's methodology in different contexts.

Explain how partners intend to:
continue cooperating after the project;
organise follow-up activities;
develop new initiatives based on the project;
integrate successful practices into future Erasmus+ projects and organisational strategies;
seek additional funding or institutional support where appropriate.

general_context:
This question belongs primarily to the Impact award criterion and focuses on the breadth and significance of the project's impact.
The evaluator wants to understand who will benefit from the project and how far its effects will extend beyond the direct participants and consortium.
In simple terms, the evaluator is asking:
"Who will benefit from this project, how will they benefit, and how will the project's impact extend beyond the partnership?"
This question goes beyond immediate project results. The evaluator is looking for evidence that the project will generate positive changes at multiple levels, including the participating organisations, their staff, target groups, stakeholders, and wider society.
Many beginners focus only on the direct participants or state that "all partners will benefit equally." While all organisations should gain value from participating, the impact will often differ depending on each partner's role, expertise, and organisational context.
A strong answer demonstrates:
the impact on each participating organisation;
how benefits are shared across the partnership;
how the project reaches external stakeholders;
how the results create value at local, regional, national and European levels;
how the impact can continue growing through dissemination and exploitation.
The evaluator wants to see that the project creates a multiplier effect rather than benefiting only those directly involved.

writing_guidance:
By the time evaluators reach this question, they already know:
the project objectives;
the planned activities;
the expected results;
the dissemination strategy;
the sustainability plan.
Now they want to understand:
How large will the project's impact be?
A strong answer usually considers several levels of impact:
individual impact;
organisational impact;
partnership impact;
community impact;
sectoral impact;
European impact.
Not every organisation will experience exactly the same type of impact, but every partner should obtain meaningful and lasting benefits that reflect its role within the project.

criteria.elements:
Explain how participation will contribute to:
organisational development;
staff competences;
innovation;
internationalisation;
improved services;
new methodologies;
stronger European cooperation.
Where appropriate, explain that while all partners benefit, the type and scale of impact may differ according to their expertise, responsibilities, and organisational needs.

Describe how the project will benefit:
learners;
educators;
trainers;
youth workers;
educational institutions;
NGOs;
public authorities;
community organisations;
professional networks;
policy makers;
other Erasmus+ beneficiaries.
Explain how dissemination, open resources, multiplier events, networks, and stakeholder engagement will allow additional organisations and individuals to benefit from the project.

Structure the answer by describing potential impact at:
local level;
regional level;
national level;
European level.
Explain how project activities, dissemination, cooperation, and exploitation will contribute to positive changes at each level.

Explain how:
participants will transfer knowledge to colleagues;
organisations will continue using the results;
stakeholders will adopt project methodologies;
future projects will build upon the project's achievements;
dissemination and sustainability actions will continuously increase the project's reach.
Emphasise that the project's impact will grow over time rather than ending with the final project meeting.

general_context:
This question belongs primarily to the Impact criterion and focuses on the project's dissemination and exploitation strategy.
The evaluator wants to understand how the consortium will ensure that the project's results reach the people and organisations that can benefit from them.
In simple terms, the evaluator is asking:
"How will you make sure that people know about your project and actually use its results?"
Dissemination is much more than publishing news on social media or creating a website. Erasmus+ expects projects to actively promote their results so that they can be used, adapted, and transferred by other organisations, professionals, and stakeholders.
Many beginners answer this question by simply listing communication tools such as:
website;
Facebook;
newsletters;
multiplier events.
However, the evaluator is not looking for a list of dissemination channels. Instead, they want to understand:
what will be disseminated;
who will receive the information;
when dissemination will take place;
how different audiences will be reached;
how dissemination will contribute to the long-term impact of the project.
A strong answer demonstrates that dissemination is a planned and continuous process running throughout the project, rather than a few promotional actions carried out at the end.

writing_guidance:
By the time evaluators reach this question, they already know:
the project objectives;
the planned activities;
the expected results;
the sustainability strategy;
the expected impact.
Now they want to understand:
How will these results become visible, accessible, and useful to others?
A strong dissemination strategy usually includes several stages:
internal communication within the partnership;
dissemination to direct beneficiaries;
engagement with local and regional stakeholders;
promotion at national and European levels;
long-term exploitation of the project results after the project has ended.
The evaluator wants confidence that the project's outcomes will not remain within the consortium but will generate wider benefits.

criteria.elements:
Explain how dissemination will take place:
before activities begin (raising awareness);
during implementation (sharing progress);
after key milestones (promoting results);
after project completion (supporting long-term use).
Describe dissemination as a continuous process integrated into project management.

Identify the main target groups, for example:
direct participants;
educators;
trainers;
youth workers;
schools;
universities;
NGOs;
public authorities;
employers;
policy makers;
European networks;
local communities;
the general public.
Explain how different dissemination methods will be adapted to the needs of different audiences.

Describe an appropriate combination of activities, such as:
project website;
social media;
newsletters;
news articles;
conferences;
workshops;
multiplier events;
stakeholder meetings;
professional networks;
educational platforms;
open-access repositories;
partner communication channels.
Rather than simply listing channels, explain how each contributes to reaching different audiences.

Explain how dissemination will:
encourage organisations to use the developed resources;
promote the transfer of methodologies;
support replication in other contexts;
strengthen European cooperation;
contribute to sustainability beyond the project's lifetime.
Show that dissemination is closely linked to exploitation of results rather than simply increasing publicity.
